   <title>
    <narrative xml:lang="EN">Prevention and response to COVID-19 pandemic related to WASH</narrative>
   </title>
   <reference code="WSH-COV-R7" vocabulary="99" vocabulary-uri="https://dutchrelief.org"></reference>
   <indicator aggregation-status="1" ascending="1" measure="1">
    <title>
     <narrative xml:lang="EN">Number of people receiving&#xA0;COVID-19 related assistance (WASH).</narrative>
    </title>
    <description>
     <narrative xml:lang="EN">In Alimbongo and Bunyakiri, WV will install 142 hand-washing stations at HCs, 64 at frequented places in communities (pharmacies, schools when open) and 40 at hospitals. Soap, disinfectant and chlorine are supplied monthly, which can be adapted to higher stocks and less movements in case Covid19 worsens. 12,300 (6,396 female and 5,904 male) will be enabled to practice good hand-washing practices to protect themselves from infection. 
- 15 HCs and 2 hospitals will be equipped with PPE (including thermo-flash, medical clothing, respiratory protection) to protect medical personnel and patients from infection and enable to detect symptoms. 
- WV will train 48 religious leaders on WV&#x2019;s Channels of Hope approach and form Community Hope Action Team (CHATs). Faith leaders will be trained on providing MHPSS through messages/phone calls addressing fears of the disease and secondary effects. 108 CHAT representatives will support faith leaders. 
- Local partners will support faith leaders in disseminating prevention messages and producing radio spots. The project will sign contracts with 14 radios (7 in North Kivu and 7 in South Kivu) to emit radio spots to reach 34,712 female and 32,041 male (total: 66,753) in Bunyakiri and 50,372 female and 42,508 male in Alimbongo and Lubero (total: 92,880)
- Local partners will train 10 CHWs per HA (160 CHWs in total) to conduct door-to-door visits in the communities for prevention promotion and symptoms detection. 1 CHW covers 15 HH on average, i.e. 16 HA * 10 CHWs/HA * 15 HH/CHW * 6 persons/HH = 14,400 people (7,488 female and 6,912 male)
- 30 posters with Covid19-messages will be hung up at frequented spots (health centers, pharmacies, junctions etc.) in each health area (total: 240 posters).</narrative>
    </description>
